The mean NPV of 13,586 CHF indicates a favorable expected return, with a median of 10,066 CHF. The 10th percentile (worst case) shows -35,075 CHF, while the 90th percentile (best case) reaches 68,044 CHF.

Methodology

Monte Carlo Simulation Approach

This analysis uses Monte Carlo simulation to assess the uncertainty and risk associated with the Engelberg property investment. The simulation randomly varies four critical parameters across their plausible ranges to generate 10,000 different scenarios.

Parameters Varied

  • Occupancy Rate: Uniform distribution from 30% to 70% (base case: ~61.5%)
  • Average Daily Rate: Uniform distribution from 200 to 400 CHF (base case: ~324 CHF)
  • Interest Rate: Uniform distribution from 1.2% to 3.5% (base case: 1.9%)
  • Property Management Fee Rate: Uniform distribution from 20% to 35% (base case: 30%)

Simulation Process

  • For each simulation, random values are drawn from uniform distributions for all four parameters
  • A complete 15-year financial projection is calculated for each scenario
  • NPV and IRR are computed using a 5% discount rate
  • Results are aggregated to show probability distributions and key statistics

Assumptions Held Constant

  • Property purchase price: 1,300,000 CHF
  • Loan-to-value ratio: 75%
  • Amortization rate: 1.0%
  • Inflation rate: 2% per year
  • Property appreciation: 1% per year
  • Other operating expenses (insurance, utilities, maintenance reserve)
